"after 13 November 1390":"na 13 november 1390","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1376":"1376","13 November 1390":"13 november 1390","1365":"1365","1397":"1397","1390":"1390","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Schotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Canisbay, Highlands, Scotland":"Canisbay, Caithness, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1376–13 November 1390":"1376–13 November 1390","1365–1435":"1365–1435","1390–1458":"1390–1458","1397–1458":"1397–1458","1376–1390":"1376–1390","after 13 November 1390":"after 13 November 1390","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1376":"1376","13 November 1390":"13 November 1390","1365":"1365","1397":"1397","1390":"1390","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Schotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Canisbay, Highlands, Scotland":"Canisbay, Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nicholson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Nic(h)olas</i> or the vernacular form <i>Nic(h)ol</i> + <i>son</i>; see   Nichol  ,   Nicholas  . In Scotland the name was sometimes substituted for   McNichol  .","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Nicolaisen   or   Nikolaisen  , or of the Swedish cognate <b>Niklasson</b>, patronymics from equivalents of the personal name   Nicholas  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolson","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Nicholson  ."]},{"name":"Nichelson","meanings":["Variant of   Nicholson  ."]},{"name":"Nicolson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Iain, Murdo.","English and Northern Scottish: variant of   Nicholson  ."]},{"name":"Nichol","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Nic(h)ol(e)</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Nic(h)olas</i> (see   Nicholas  ). Compare   Nickel   and   Nicol  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Greek   Nikolas  , its variant   Nicolas  , or of any of various derivatives of the personal name <i>Nikola(o)s</i> ‘Nicholas’, including <b>Nikolis</b> (see   Nicoli  ). Compare   Nicholas   and   Nicol  ."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jean Nicholson was born in 1376, in Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married John Mowat in 1396, in Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died on 13 November 1390, in Canisbay, Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 14, and was buried in Canisbay, Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1376–13 November 1390":"1376–13. november 1390","1365–1435":"1365–1435","1390–1458":"1390–1458","1397–1458":"1397–1458","1376–1390":"1376–1390",